AMENDED AND RESTATED SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT
THIS AMENDED AND RESTATED SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT made as of November 15, 2016 between Algonquin SKIC 20 Solar, LLC ("SKIC20") and Algonquin SKIC 10 Solar, LLC ("SKIC10"). SKIC20 and SKIC10 are referred to herein individually as a "Party" and collectively as the "Parties".
WHEREAS:
A. SKIC20 entered into a Shared Facilities Agreement dated as of April 30, 2014 (the "Original Agreement") with TC Valos Solar Energy, LLC ("TC Valos"). TC Valos assigned its rights and obligations under the Original Agreement to SKIC10 pursuant to that certain Assignment and Assumption Agreement, dated as of March 10, 2015. The Parties wish to amend and restate the Original Agreement in its entirety.
B. SKIC20 owns a solar generating facility consisting of photovoltaic panels, inverters, a tracker system, a collection system (the "SKIC20 PV Facility"), a transmission line (the "SKIC20 Transmission Line"), and a substation interconnecting the facility to the California ISO electrical grid (the "SKIC20 Substation") and certain Permits (defined herein), land rights, access roads associated therewith (collectively, the SKIC20 PV Facility, the SKIC20 Transmission Line and the SKIC20 Substation will be referred to as the "SKIC20 Project").
C. SKIC10 wishes to install a solar generation facility adjacent to the SKIC20 Project, consisting of photovoltaic panels, inverters, a tracker system, a collection system (the "SKIC10 PV Facility"), a transmission line (the "SKIC10 Transmission Line"), and a substation interconnecting the facility to the California ISO electrical grid (the "SKIC10 Substation") and certain Permits, land rights, access roads associated therewith (collectively, the SKIC10 PV Facility, the SKIC10 Transmission Line and the SKIC10 Substation will be referred to as the "SKIC10 Project") and interconnect the SKIC10 Project with the California ISO electrical grid using the Shared Facilities (as defined herein).
D. The Parties wish to enter into this Agreement to set out their respective rights and obligations with respect to the joint use of the Shared Facilities (as defined below).
NOW THEREFORE in consideration of the agreements of the Parties herein and for other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which are hereby acknowledged, the Parties agree as follows:
ARTICLE 1 DEFINITIONS AND INTERPRETATION 1.1 Definitions In this Agreement, unless there is something in the subject matter or context inconsistent therewith, the following terms shall have the respective meanings set out below: "Affiliate" means, with respect to any Person, any other Person directly or indirectly Controlled by, Controlling, or under common Control with, the first Person.
"Agreement" means this Amended and Restated Shared Facilities Agreement, as the same may be amended, restated, modified or supplemented from time to time.
"Annual Plan" has the meaning given to it in Section 3.5.
"Applicable Laws" means with respect to any Person, property, transaction or event, all federal, provincial, municipal or regional laws, by-laws, statutes, rules, regulations, Orders, judgments, awards, decrees, decisions, codes, policies, rulings, conditions of any license, Permit or other requirements having the force of law relating to or applicable to such Person, property, transaction or event.
"Business Day" means any day other than a Saturday, a Sunday or a statutory holiday in the State of California.
"Control" of any Person means:
(i) with respect to any corporation or other Person having voting shares or the equivalent, the ownership or power to vote, directly or indirectly, shares, or the equivalent, representing 50% or more of the power to vote in the election of directors, managers or persons performing similar functions;
(ii) ownership of 50% or more of the equity or beneficial interest in that Person; or
(iii) the ability to direct the business and affairs of any Person by acting as a general partner, manager or otherwise,
and "Controlled" and "Controlling" shall have corresponding meanings.
"Dispute" has the meaning set out in Section 9.5.
"Easements" means collectively, the Franchise Agreement and the Utility Easement.
"Emergency" has the meaning set out in Section 3.6.
"Encumbrance" means any lien, mortgage, charge, security interest, debenture, encumbrance or any other arrangement under which any of the interest of SKIC20 in and to the SKIC20 Property, or SKIC10 in and to the SKIC10 Property, becomes security for any indebtedness or other obligation.
"Force Majeure" means any event beyond the reasonable control of the Party claiming Force Majeure, including (i) acts of God, catastrophic ice, sand and other storms, lightning, floods, earthquakes, volcanic eruptions and landslides; (ii) strikes, lockouts and other industrial disturbances; (iii) epidemics, war (whether or not declared), blockades, acts of public enemies, acts of sabotage or terrorism, civil insurrection, riots and civil disobedience; (iv) acts or omissions of any Governmental Authority (so long as the Party claiming Force Majeure has not applied or assisted in any application for any such action or omission), including delays in regulatory process and Orders of a Governmental Authority; and (v) explosions and fires not covered by insurance.
"Franchise Agreement" means Resolution No. 2014-097, approved on April 1, 2014, by the Board of Supervisors, County of Kern, State of California, granting a pole line transmission system and underground fiber optic cable franchise to SKIC Solar, LLC pursuant to the Franchise Act of 1937 and Government Code Section 26001, as assigned to SKIC20, and as the same may be amended from time to time.
"Governmental Authority" means any (i) multinational, federal, state, regional, municipal, local or other government or public entity, domestic or foreign, (ii) any subdivision or authority of any of the foregoing, (iii) any Person, court, tribunal, arbitrator, arbitration tribunal, agency, board, commission, central bank, bureau, agency or department, exercising executive, legislative, judicial, regulatory, expropriation, taxing or other administrative functions of, or pertaining to, government or having jurisdiction in the relevant circumstances.
"Independent Engineer" means Blue Oak Energy, LLC or such other independent engineer as may be agreed by the Parties in writing.
"Maintenance and Repair" means ongoing maintenance, repairs, upgrades, servicing and replacements, both operational and capital, and including regular preventative maintenance, repairs and servicing due to damage, destruction or wear and tear of the Shared Facilities.
"Maintenance and Repair Dispute" has the meaning set out in Section 3.7.
"Orders" means all applicable orders, decisions or other binding directives rendered by any Governmental Authority.
"Per MW Basis" means a pro-rata calculation based on each Party's respective installed nameplate capacity, in megawatts, and the combined total installed nameplate capacity of the SKIC10 Project and the SKIC20 Project.
"Permits" means all permits, licenses, certificates of authorization, authorizations, certificates of approval, approvals and registrations granted by a Governmental Authority.
"Person" means and includes individuals, corporations, limited partnerships, general partnerships, joint stock companies, unlimited liability corporations, banks, trust companies, trusts or any other organization, whether or not legal entities and any Governmental Authority.
"PG&E" means Pacific Gas & Electric Company, a California corporation.
"Power Purchase Agreement" means, in respect of SKIC20, the SKIC20 Power Purchase Agreement, and in the case of SKIC10, the SKIC10 Power Purchase Agreement as each such agreement may be supplemented, amended or restated from time to time. "Project Property" means, collectively, the SKIC20 Property and the SKIC10 Property.
"Prudent Utility Practice" means, at a particular time, in the exercise of reasonable judgment in light of the facts known at the time a decision was made, those practices, standards, designs, methods, means, techniques, equipment and acts that would require one to: (a) perform its duties in good faith and as a reasonably prudent operator of solar energy projects taking into account the need to maintain qualification of the project for renewable energy investment tax credit, (b) exercise such care, skill and diligence as a reasonably prudent business company of established reputation engaged in the solar energy business would exercise in the conduct of its business and for the advancement or protection of its own interests, (c) perform the duties in accordance with applicable solar energy industry standards in the same region as the project, (d) use sufficient and properly trained and skilled personnel, (e) comply with the terms and provisions of the (i) SKIC10 Interconnection Agreement, and the (ii) SKIC20 Interconnection Agreement; and (f) follow, or cause the applicable third parties to follow, applicable vendor recommendations, instructions, guidelines and manuals and maintain such records, in each case, to the extent necessary in order to avoid the invalidation of product and service warranties relating to materials or equipment provided to the project and any exclusions under the terms of such warranties, in all cases with respect to clauses (a) through (e) herein. Prudent Utility Practices are not intended to be limited to optimum practice or methods to the exclusion of all others, but rather to be a spectrum of reasonable and prudent practices and methods that must take the conditions specific to any given facility into consideration.
"Shared Communications Facilities" means the equipment that is shared by the SKIC10 Project and the SKIC20 Project to provide voice and data communication in and out of each project. The Shared Communications Facilities include an underground fiber optic cable between the SKIC20 substation control building and the Copper Fiber Junction box located across Copus Road from PG&E's Copus Substation, together with the associated terminal equipment at each end of the underground fiber optic cable, a fiber optic cable strung along the Shared Pole Line between the control building located at the SKIC20 Substation and inverter station RPS#5 at the SKIC20 PV Facility, and communications equipment installed in the SKIC20 Substation control building to facilitate communications for the SKIC10 Project and the SKIC20 Project including connection to the Internet and to the California Independent System Operator Corporation's ECN Network.
"Shared Facilities" has the meaning set out in Section 2.1.
"Shared Interconnection Facilities" means the equipment that is shared by the SKIC10 Project and the SKIC20 Project and located in and directly adjacent to the SKIC10 Substation and SKIC20 Substation to provide interconnection between both projects and PG&E's 70kV "Copus to Old River" transmission line. The Shared Interconnection Facilities include the steel pole at the Point of Change of Ownership, as defined in the Interconnection Agreement (the "PCO Pole"), a steel H-frame dead-end structure, the conductors from the PCO Pole to the dead-end structure, a 3-phase 70kV disconnect switch labeled SW-23 and mounted on the dead-end structure, a 72.5kV circuit breaker labeled CB-22, three single-phase 70 kV voltage transformers labeled VT-L1, VT-L2, and VT-L3, a 70kV common wire bus including conductors, insulators, and steel support structures, and all the associated protection and control equipment for the above equipment and located inside the control buildings located in the SKIC10 Substation and SKIC20 Substation.
"Shared Pole Line" means a monopole transmission line designed to accommodate two transmission circuits from the southwest corner of the SKIC20 PV Facility to the SKIC20 Substation and consisting of steel and wood poles and all necessary and proper anchors, guy wires, foundations, footings, cross-arms, insulators and other appliances and fixtures for use in connection with said poles. The circuit conductors suspended from the Shared Pole Line poles do not form part of the Shared Pole Line.
"SKIC10 Access Rights" has the meaning set out in Section 4.1(a). "SKIC10 Indemnified Party" has the meaning set out in Section 7.2.
"SKIC10 Interconnection Agreement" means the Small Generator Interconnection Agreement (SGIA-GIDAP), dated as of November 5, 2014, by and among SKIC10 (as assignee of TC Valos Solar Energy, LLC), PG&E, and the California Independent System Operator Corporation, as amended or restated from time to time.
"SKIC10 Lines" has the meaning set out in Section 2.1(b).
"SKIC10 Power Purchase Agreement" means the Power Purchase Agreement dated September 30, 2014 in respect of the SKIC10 Project between SKIC10 and Southern California Edison Company, as such agreement may be supplemented, amended or restated from time to time.
"SKIC10 Project" has the meaning set out in Recital C.
"SKIC10 Property" means all right, title and interest of SKIC10 in the lands and premises forming part of the SKIC10 Project, as generally described in Schedule B, and all appurtenances thereto, including SKIC10's rights hereunder.
"SKIC10 Substation Equipment" means the step-up transformer, metering equipment, interconnection equipment and certain other equipment to be owned by SKIC10 relating to the SKIC10 Project on site at the SKIC10 Substation.
"SKIC20 Access Rights" has the meaning set out in Section 4.2(a). "SKIC20 Indemnified Party" has the meaning set out in Section 7.1.
"SKIC20 Interconnection Agreement" means the Small Generator Interconnection Agreement Small Generator Interconnection Agreement by and among SKIC20, Pacific Gas & Electric Company and CAISO dated August 16, 2013, as amended or restated from time to time.
"SKIC20 Project" has the meaning set out in Recital B.
"SKIC20 Power Purchase Agreement" means the Power Purchase Agreement dated August 30, 2012 in respect of the SKIC20 Project between SKIC20 and PG&E, as such agreement may be supplemented, amended or restated from time to time. "SKIC20 Property" means all right, title and interest of SKIC20 in the lands and premises forming part of the SKIC20 Project, as generally described in Schedule A, and all appurtenances thereto, including the Shared Facilities.
"SKIC20 PV Facility" is defined in Recital B.
"Spare Parts and Consumables" means commercially reasonable supplies of spare parts and consumables required in connection with routine Maintenance and Repair of the Shared Facilities.
"Term" has the meaning set out in Section 8.1.
"Transfer" means any lease, sublease, assignment, sale, conveyance or any other disposition of all or any part of the SKIC20 Property or all or any part of the SKIC10 Property (including expropriation and transfer by operation of Applicable Law).
"Transferee" has the meaning set out in Section 5.1.
"Transferor" has the meaning set out in Section 5.1.
"Utility Easement" means that certain utility easement granted to SKIC Development Company, LLC by South Kern Industrial Center, LLC dated July 22, 2010, recorded on July 28, 2010 with the Kern County Recorder's Office as Document #0210099449, as assigned to SKIC20.
1.2 Headings and Preamble for Reference Only The headings preceding the Articles and sections hereof have been inserted for convenience and reference only and shall not be construed to affect the meaning, construction or effect of this Agreement. The preamble and recitals hereto (and all definitions therein contained) shall form an integral part of this Agreement.
1.3 Interpretation In this Agreement, unless the context otherwise requires, words importing the singular include the plural and vice versa, and words importing gender include all genders.
1.4 Currency Except as otherwise may be expressly provided in this Agreement, all amounts in this Agreement are stated and shall be paid in U.S. Dollars.
1.5 Severability The provisions of this Agreement are severable, and if any provisions are in conflict with any Applicable Laws, the conflicting provisions shall be deemed never to have constituted a part of this Agreement and shall not affect or impair any of the remaining provisions hereof. If any provision of this Agreement shall be held invalid or unenforceable in any jurisdiction, such invalidity or unenforceability shall attach only to such provision in such jurisdiction and shall not in any manner affect or render invalid or unenforceable such provision in any other jurisdiction or any other provision of this Agreement in any jurisdiction.
1.6 Entire Agreement This Agreement constitutes the entire agreement between the Parties pertaining to the subject matter of this Agreement.
1.7 Accounting Terms All accounting terms not specifically defined herein shall be construed in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles in the United States, and any reference herein to generally accepted accounting principles shall mean such principles consistently applied from year to year, to the extent possible.
1.8 References to Include Successors and Assigns Except as otherwise provided herein, the provisions of this Agreement enure to the benefit of, and shall be binding upon, the Parties and their respective successors and permitted assigns.
1.9 Waiver, Amendment Except as expressly provided in this Agreement, no amendment or waiver of this Agreement shall be binding unless executed in writing by the Party or Parties to be bound thereby. No waiver of any provision of this Agreement shall constitute a waiver of any other provision, nor shall any waiver of any provision of this Agreement constitute a continuing waiver, unless otherwise expressly provided.
1.10 Governing Law This Agreement shall be interpreted and governed by and be construed exclusively in accordance with the laws of the State of California, regardless of the laws that might otherwise govern under applicable principles of conflicts of laws thereof.
1.11 Certain Phrases, etc. In this Agreement, the words "including" and "includes" mean "including (or includes) without limitation".
1.12 Business Days If any payment is required to be made or other action is required to be taken pursuant to this Agreement on a day which is not a Business Day, then such payment or action shall be made or taken on the next Business Day.
1.13 Schedules The following Schedules are attached hereto and are incorporated in and are deemed to be an integral part of this Agreement:
Schedule A: Description of the SKIC20 Property
Schedule B: Description of the SKIC10 Property
ARTICLE 2 SHARED FACILITIES 2.1 Shared Pole Line, Shared Interconnection Facilities, Shared Communications Facilities, and SKIC10 Substation Equipment (a) The Parties agree that the Shared Pole Line will form part of the SKIC20 Project and the SKIC10 Project. (b) The actual three-phase, 34.5 kV circuit conductors for the SKIC10 Project (the "SKIC10 Lines") shall be owned by SKIC10. SKIC10 has the right to operate and maintain the SKIC10 Lines on the Shared Pole Line in accordance with the terms of this Agreement and prudent industry practice. SKIC20 will have the right to select the equipment to be used for the Shared Pole Line, in its sole discretion but in accordance with Prudent Industry Practice. (c) The Parties acknowledge and agree that the equipment and infrastructure set out below (collectively, the "Shared Facilities") are shared between the SKIC20 Project and the SKIC10 Project and that the use, operation, maintenance, repair, replacement and insurance of the Shared Facilities by the Parties shall be governed by the provisions of this Agreement: (i) The Shared Pole Line; (ii) The Shared Interconnection Facilities; and, (iii) The Shared Communications Facilities. (d) Except to the extent of suspension, constraint, curtailment or outage of electrical energy required due to an Emergency, occurring as a consequence of Force Majeure or for Maintenance and Repair of the Shared Facilities in accordance with the terms of this Agreement, and without limiting Section 2.1(a) or (b): (i) each Party shall be entitled to continuous and uninterrupted use of the Shared Facilities as necessary or desirable to conduct its business of supplying electricity under its Power Purchase Agreement; (ii) neither Party shall interfere with access to, or the common use, operation and peaceful enjoyment of, the Shared Facilities by the other Party; and (iii) SKIC10's rights to access, and the use, operation and enjoyment of, the Shared Facilities shall be substantively the same as SKIC20's rights to access, use, operate and enjoy the Shared Facilities. (e) SKIC10 acknowledges that the Shared Pole Line is located on lands that are the subject of the Easements, and any access and use of such SKIC20 Property must be in accordance with ARTICLE 4 of this Agreement. 2.2 Separate Projects Except as expressly provided herein, the SKIC20 Project and the SKIC10 Project shall be operated as two separate and distinct projects. Without limiting the foregoing:
(a) SKIC10 shall not cause or permit any Encumbrances (other than Encumbrances permitted pursuant to Section 5.2) created by or through SKIC10 to be made against all or part of the SKIC20 Project which relate to any obligation of SKIC10; (b) SKIC20 shall not cause or permit any Encumbrances created by or through SKIC20 to be made against all or part of the SKIC10 Project which relate to any obligation of SKIC20; (c) all operating costs that are directly attributable to the SKIC20 Project or the SKIC10 Project and not to the Shared Facilities shall be paid by SKIC20 or SKIC10, respectively; and (d) costs and expenses related to services or equipment specific to the SKIC20 Project or the SKIC10 Project shall be paid by SKIC20 or SKIC10, respectively. 2.3 Permits The Parties confirm that a Permit, specifically the conditional use permit, has been issued by the applicable Governmental Authority in respect of the land for both the SKIC20 Project and the SKIC10 Project. Each Party is responsible for securing any Permits required in connection with its project, and each Party agrees to reasonably co-operate with the other to facilitate obtaining any such Permits.
ARTICLE 3 MAINTENANCE AND REPAIR; COST SHARING; CURTAILMENT 3.1 Maintenance and Repair Subject to this Article ARTICLE 3, SKIC20 shall be solely responsible for the sourcing, oversight and completion of all Maintenance and Repair with respect to the Shared Facilities in accordance with Prudent Utility Practices. All maintenance and inspection services shall be performed at regular intervals in accordance with manufacturer recommendations and manuals, and requirements to preserve manufacturer warranties. All maintenance and inspection services shall be performed by qualified technical personnel.
3.2 Basic Cost Sharing Agreement The Parties will share in all Maintenance and Repair costs for the Shared Facilities (including the cost of all Spare Parts and Consumables) and all costs associated with maintaining any of the SKIC10 Access Rights. For greater certainty, the Parties anticipate that Maintenance and Repair of the Shared Facilities will include costs set forth in the Annual Plan, inspection and maintenance of major components, vegetation management within the rights-of-way, and erosion and sediment control. Except as expressly provided herein, all costs of Maintenance and Repair and maintenance of the SKIC10 Access Rights shall be shared by the Parties on a Per MW Basis.
3.3 Other Repairs and/or Upgrades Except in the case of an Emergency or as set out in the Annual Plan, the Parties will first agree upon any Maintenance and Repair costs and any replacements in excess of $25,000 and all upgrades proposed for the Shared Facilities prior to commencing same. Once approved, such repairs, replacements and upgrades will be undertaken in the manner agreed by the Parties and each Party will share such costs on a Per MW Basis. Any costs approved by SKIC10 and incurred by SKIC20 or its' Affiliate, in respect of the repair or upgrade of the SKIC10 Substation Equipment shall be borne solely by SKIC10.
3.4 Shared Costs For greater certainty, shared costs will include all applicable taxes that are properly incurred by either Party in accordance with the provisions of this Agreement in connection with Maintenance and Repair (routine or non-routine) of the Shared Facilities and will include costs for consultants, contractors, materials and equipment, and any internal costs incurred by SKIC20 in connection with the operation and maintenance services provided hereunder. SKIC20 shall invoice SKIC10 quarterly for its share of such costs on a Per MW Basis and any costs for which it is solely responsible for the previous quarter in accordance with Section 3.9. In the event that SKIC20 fails to perform any of its obligations hereunder, SKIC10 may pay any such costs, or costs to maintain the SKIC10 Access Rights, and invoice SKIC20 for its share thereof on a Per MW Basis, which SKIC20 will pay within 30 days of receipt.
3.5 Budget The Parties agree to jointly prepare, on an annual basis for each calendar year, and thereafter comply with in respect of such calendar year, a Maintenance and Repair budget and comprehensive maintenance and repair plan with respect to the Shared Facilities and the SKIC10 Substation Equipment, if applicable, which will provide for all scheduled and/or required repair and maintenance necessary for the ownership, care, control and operation (each in accordance with Prudent Industry Practices) of the Shared Facilities and the SKIC10 Substation Equipment, if applicable (the "Annual Plan").
3.6 Emergencies Each Party shall be entitled to immediately effect emergency measures to the Shared Facilities, the SKIC10 Substation Equipment or the SKIC20 Project Substation directly in the event of a situation where such Party reasonably determines that immediate action is necessary to safeguard life or property, the environment or to preserve its rights under insurance (each such occurrence, an "Emergency"), provided that, if time permits each Party must first notify the other Party in writing or orally with written notice to follow as soon as possible thereafter. The costs of making such repairs and replacements shall be shared by the Parties on a Per MW Basis, except for (a) the costs with respect to the SKIC10 Substation Equipment which shall be borne solely by SKIC10, and (b) the costs with respect to the SKIC20 Project substation which shall be borne solely by SKIC20, so long as the Party initiating the repairs or replacements has used its commercially reasonable efforts to consult with the other Party before incurring any such costs in excess of $25,000.
3.7 Disputes regarding Maintenance and Repair In the event that the Parties are unable to agree on the Annual Plan for the next calendar year by October 31, or a Party otherwise has a dispute with respect to any Maintenance and Repair matter (a "Maintenance and Repair Dispute"), either Party may submit such dispute to the Independent Engineer for final and binding determination. The Independent Engineer shall make its determination taking into account all applicable industry standards and the Parties' obligations under their respective Power Purchase Agreements and Interconnection Handbooks. The Independent Engineer shall be retained by the Parties within ten (10) Business Days following either Party providing written notice to the other Party of the Maintenance and Repair Dispute, which notice shall outline in reasonable detail the nature of the dispute. The Independent Engineer must provide its determination by written report (or a revised Annual Plan, if applicable) to the Parties within ten (10) Business Days following its appointment. The Parties will share the cost of retaining the Independent Engineer on a Per MW Basis.
3.8 Indemnification Each Party shall indemnify and compensate the other Party on an annual basis for any and all documented lost revenue, costs and expenses suffered by such Party as a result of the other project or any part of the Shared Facilities forming part of the project, including any lost revenues suffered by the project as a result of partial or full shut downs of the project during the construction or operation of the project or any part of the Shared Facilities forming part of the project, or partial or full shut downs of the project resulting from the maintenance of the project's substation equipment where such maintenance is performed by a Person other than SKIC20 or its Affiliates.
3.9 Invoicing Within thirty (30) days following the end of each calendar quarter or calendar year, as applicable, SKIC20 shall invoice SKIC10 for all amounts payable by SKIC10 to SKIC20 under this Article 4 during such period. Each such invoice shall include a detailed breakdown of the amount for which SKIC20 is seeking reimbursement or compensation under this Article 4. Such amounts shall be payable by SKIC10 to SKIC20 within 30 days of receipt by SKIC10 of the invoice.
3.10 Late Payments Any amount not paid when due and payable hereunder shall bear interest at the then current prime rate in effect at the National Bank of Canada plus one and a half percent (1.5%) per annum. Such interest shall accrue from the first day after payment is due until payment in full is made.
3.11 Curtailment (a) In the event of any curtailment initiated directly against either the SKIC20 Project under the SKIC20 Power Purchase Agreement or directly against the SKIC10 Project under the SKIC10 Power Purchase Agreement, or against either project by CAISO, such curtailment will be for the account of the project with the applicable Power Purchase Agreement or the account of the project receiving notice from CAISO and such curtailment will have no impact on the other project. (b) In the event of a curtailment against both the SKIC20 Project and the SKIC10 Project by CAISO or PG&E, the curtailment instruction shall be allocated between the SKIC20 Project and the SKIC10 Project on a Per MW Basis, except where such allocation is in violation of the applicable curtailment instruction. (c) If SKIC20, during the course of operating, maintaining, or repairing the Shared Pole Line, determines in accordance with Prudent Utility Practice, that an issue exists that would reduce the power that can be transmitted over the SKIC10 Lines incorporated in the Shared Pole Line, such as overloading, impending component failure or foreign object damage, then SKIC10 will cause the SKIC10 Project to reduce the generation of electricity as required by SKIC20 to resolve such issue; provided, however that if an issue exists on the Shared Pole Line that is a result of SKIC20's lack of maintenance or failure to repair in a timely manner the Shared Pole Line or other breach of its obligations under this Agreement, SKIC20 will indemnify SKIC10 for any and all documented lost revenue, costs and expenses suffered by SKIC10 as a result of the reduction in the generation of electricity from the SKIC10 Project over the SKIC10 Lines incorporated in the Shared Pole Line due to such failure. SKIC20 shall limit the length of any such interruption or curtailment to that time strictly necessary to correct the occurrence of a matter set forth in Section 3.11. To the extent commercially reasonable, any interruption or curtailment shall be made during periods that balance both low or no solar energy and low energy prices so as to minimize potential loss of revenue of the project being curtailed. ARTICLE 4 ACCESS RIGHTS 4.1 Access Rights to SKIC20 Property (a) SKIC20 hereby grants to SKIC10, its employees, contractors, consultants, agents and representatives, the right to access, ingress and egress to the property subject to the Franchise Agreement to the extent necessary for the inspection, operation, maintenance, repair and replacement of the SKIC10 Lines (the "SKIC10 Access Rights"), whether by lease, registered instrument, private agreement, license, right of way, convention or otherwise. (b) SKIC20 agrees that it will maintain the SKIC20 Project in good standing and will not modify or release the SKIC20 Property or the rights thereto without first receiving the prior written consent of SKIC10, which consent shall not be unreasonably withheld, conditioned or delayed unless it prohibits the continued operation of the SKIC10 Project in the ordinary course of business. (c) SKIC10 agrees that it shall comply with the terms and conditions of any underlying agreements when exercising the SKIC10 Access Rights. 4.2 Access Rights to SKIC10 Property (a) SKIC10 hereby grants to SKIC20, its employees, contractors, consultants, agents and representatives the right to access, ingress and egress to the SKIC10 Property only to the extent necessary for the limited purposes of Emergencies or inspection of the operation and maintenance of the Shared Facilities (collectively, the "SKIC20 Access Rights"), whether by lease, registered instrument, private agreement, license, right of way, convention or otherwise. (b) SKIC10 agrees that it will maintain all of the SKIC10 Project in good standing and will not modify or release the SKIC10 Property or the rights thereto without first receiving the prior written consent of SKIC20, which consent shall not be unreasonably withheld, conditioned or delayed unless it prohibits the continued operation of the SKIC20 Project in the ordinary course of business. (c) SKIC20 agrees that it shall comply with the terms and conditions of any underlying agreements when exercising the SKIC20 Access Rights. ARTICLE 5 TRANSFERS AND DEFAULT 5.1 Transfers (a) Either Party may Transfer all or any part of its interest in the Project Property or any of its rights and obligations under this Agreement if the transferor ("Transferor") obtains the prior written consent of the other Party, not to be unreasonably withheld, and obtains from any transferee, purchaser, assignee or any other Person to whom such interest is being disposed (a "Transferee") prior to or contemporaneously with the acquisition of such interest, an agreement duly executed by the Transferee, pursuant to which the Transferee shall assume all obligations of the Transferor pursuant to this Agreement, and if the Transferee is acquiring only part of the interest of the Transferor in the Project Property, such obligations shall be joint and several with the Transferor. Notwithstanding the foregoing, consent shall not be required to Transfer, but prior written notice shall be delivered, where (i) the Transferee is an Affiliate of such Party; or (ii) if the assignment is solely a collateral assignment for security purposes whereby the lender assumes the obligations of the Transferor upon a foreclosure. Any such Transferee shall be required to execute such documents as the other Party, or its lender, may reasonably require. (b) All rights and liabilities herein extend to and bind the Parties and their respective successors and assigns, as permitted pursuant to this Agreement. 5.2 Title This Agreement shall not operate to transfer any right, title or interest of either Party to the other and title to any Shared Facilities will remain the property of each such Party and their permitted assigns. Other than the rights of the Parties provided herein, each Party will ensure that its respective interest in the Shared Facilities and this Agreement remains free and clear of any Encumbrances, other than the granting of an Encumbrance to a third party lender or lenders in connection with financing provided to or for the benefit of such Party, so long as such Encumbrance is subject and subordinated to the rights of the Parties under this Agreement.
ARTICLE 6 FORCE MAJEURE SKIC20 shall promptly notify SKIC10 if there is an event of Force Majeure. Such notice shall describe the event of Force Majeure, the corrective action to be taken, and the estimated time of the Force Majeure interruption. If SKIC20 is prevented from performing any of its obligations hereunder, in whole or in part, by reason of Force Majeure, it shall be excused from performance for so long as and to the extent that Force Majeure shall so prevent its performance, it being agreed that in no case shall either Party be prevented from performing its obligation to make any payments hereunder by reason of Force Majeure. During the pendency of any Force Majeure, SKIC20 shall use commercially reasonable efforts to restore its ability to perform hereunder. SKIC20 shall be excused from the consequences of an event of Force Majeure, except for consequences resulting from the acts or omissions of SKIC20, its employees, subcontractors, agents and other representatives.

Seller makes electric energy, capacity, and ancillary services available under this Tariff to any purchaser, except as prohibited below.
2) Rates
All sales shall be made at rates established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller.
3) Other Terms and Conditions
All other terms and conditions for sales under this Tariff shall be established by agreement between Seller and purchaser.
4) Seller Category
Seller is a Category 2 seller in the Southwest region and a Category 1 seller in all other regions as defined in 18 CFR 35.36(a).
5) Compliance with Commission Regulations
Seller shall comply with the provisions of 18 CFR Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning Seller's market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes Seller to engage in affiliate sales under this Tariff or otherwise restricts or limits the Seller's market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 CFR Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning Seller's market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this Tariff.
6) Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority
Seller has received waiver of: Subparts B and C of Part 35, except for sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15 and 35.16; Part 41, Part 101 (with the exception that any waiver of the provisions of Part 101 that apply to hydropower licenses is not granted with respect to licensed hydropower projects), and Part 141, except sections 141.14 and 141.15.; and received blanket approval pursuant to Federal Power Act Section 204 and Part 34 of the Commission's regulations. Algonquin SKIC 20 Solar, LLC, ER16-2169-000 (2016).
7) Ancillary Services
PJM: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, energy imbalance service, and operating reserve service (which includes spinning, 10-minute, and 30-minute reserves) for sale into the market administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. ("PJM") and, where the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff permits, the self-supply of these services to purchasers for a bilateral sale that is used to satisfy the ancillary services requirements of the PJM Office of Interconnection.
New York: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute non-synchronous, 30-minute operating reserves, 10-minute spinning reserves, and 10-minute non-spinning reserves) for sale to purchasers in the market administered by the New York Independent System Operator, Inc.
New England: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service (automatic generator control), operating reserve service (which includes 10-minute spinning reserve, 10-minute non-spinning reserve, and 30-minute operating reserve service) to purchasers within the markets administered by the ISO New England, Inc.
California: Seller offers regulation service, spinning reserve service, and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation ("CAISO") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO.
MISO: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. (MISO) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to MISO.
Southwest Power Pool: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. (SPP) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to SPP.
Third-party ancillary services: Seller offers Regulation and Frequency Response Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, and Operating Reserve-Supplemental. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation and Frequency Response Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider's OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization.
8) Revisions
Seller may file revisions of this Tariff with the Commission. Nothing contained in this Tariff shall be construed as affecting or limiting in any way the right of Seller to unilaterally file with the Commission for a change in any aspect of this Tariff under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act pursuant to the Commission's Rules and Regulations.
9) Effective Date
This Tariff shall become effective on the date specified by the Commission.
